lb|*mWhat is this hand worth (Bergen Starting Points)?  
Example 1: @sJ5  @hAK10983  @dK873  @c7^14~13~12^2|nt||cp|2|at|^b@2

Here is the arithmetic:     @sJ5  @hAK10983  @dK873  @c7

a) You have 11 HCP
b) PLUS 2 points for the @h length
c) PLUS 1 point for the good (3 of the top 5 in a 4+ card suit) 
d) PLUS 0 point for what Marty calls “Adjust 3” 
e) MINUS 1 for the unsupported spade jack. 
=> 11 + 2 + 1 + 0 -1 = 13 STARTING points. 

If this seems confusing,  it’ll get easier as you practice it. I recommend dealing hands and evaluating them. 
So you open 1@H on this sound minimum opener.

The ^*Uadjust 3^*N works like this:
Count up the number of Aces and 10's. Then subtract the number of Quacks (Queens and Jack's) in your hand.  
If the number is +3 or more, add 1 point to your hand's value.  
If it's 6 or more, add 2 points.|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


at|
If the count is -3, or less, subtract 1 and if it's -6 or less, subtract 2. 
There is no adjust 3 on this 1st example hand:
2 (Aces and 10's)   -   1 (one J)  =   +1   => no adjust|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


at|

We use this (system) because in the 4-3-2-1 point count system, Aces and 10's are undervalued.   
And Quacks are overvalued 
If you have more Quacks than undervalued Aces and 10's, your point count is inflated, 
and you need to discount the point count.. |
